# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
- First direction of thinking was in direction of using a stack, since it will give the words of string in reverse manner.
- That is also a feasible solution, but this is quite easy approach.
- To have variables to store number of spaces and count of the words.
- And after that just return the absolute of difference.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- Iterate over the string from the back, if its space, space_variable++, count++.
- else flag=1 (encountered character) count++;
- if s[i]==space and flag=1 means this is starting of another word, which is useless for us so break the iteration.
- return absolute difference b/w space and count. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Method 1
```
class Solution {
public:
    int lengthOfLastWord(string s) {
        int n=s.length();
        int count=0;
        int space=0;
        int flag=0;
        for(int i=n-1;i>=0;i--)
        {
            if(s[i]==' ' && flag==0)
            {
                space++;
            }
            else if(s[i]!=' ')
            {
                flag=1;
            }
            else if(s[i]==' ' && flag==1){
                break;
            }
            count++;
        }
        return abs(space-count);  
    }
};
```

# Method 2
```
class Solution {
public:
    int lengthOfLastWord(string s) {
      stack<char> s1;
      int count=0;
      for(int i=0;i<s.size();i++){
          s1.push(s[i]);
      }

    while(s1.top()==' ')s1.pop();
      while(!s1.empty()&&s1.top()!=' '){
        count++;
        s1.pop();

    }
    return count;

    }
};
```

