solutions.content:
Initially I went for a simple left to right approach, using 4 variables:
* `len` stores the length of `s`;
* `tmp`, that starts at index `0` and then gets moved to the beginning of the next word with an initialy loop;
* `start` that stores the position of beginning of that word;
* `finish` that gets moved to the end of the word and stores that position;

Then I would use a `while` loop to routinely update this values as long as `tmp` is less than `len`.

Once I am done, I will have the coordinates of the last word and then just return `finish - start` :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int lengthOfLastWord(string s) {
        int start = 0, finish = 0, tmp = 0, len = s.size();
        // moving tmp to the beginning of the next word and storing it in tmp
        while (tmp < len && s[tmp] == ' ') tmp++;
        while (tmp < len) {
            // updating start
            start = tmp;
            // moving finish to the end of the next word
            finish = start + 1;
            while (finish < len && s[finish] != ' ') finish++;
            // preparing the next loop
            tmp = finish + 1;
            while (tmp < len && s[tmp] == ' ') tmp++;
        }
        return finish - start;
    }
};
```

Then it occurred to me that I was just being silly, moving left to right and that it would make much more sense go the other way around. Lesson lernt and came up with this:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int lengthOfLastWord(string s) {
        // edge case out
        if (!s.size()) return 0;
        int start, finish = s.size() - 1;
        // moving finish to the end of the last word
        while (finish && s[finish] == ' ') finish--;
        // moving start to the end of the last word
        start = finish;
        while (start > -1 && s[start] != ' ') start--;
        return finish - start;
    }
};
```

Surprisingly, the code does not run much better on average - probably because the test strings are with too few words; memory consumption is a bit lower.

