# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
- We can start iterating the characters of the string from the end and count the length of the last word.
- We skip any leading spaces and start counting when we encounter a non-space character.
- We stop counting when we encounter a space character after counting at least one non-space character.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Initialize two variables: ans to store the length of the last word and found to keep track of whether any non-space character has been found.
2. Iterate through the characters of the input string s in reverse order, starting from the last character.
3. If the current character is a space and no non-space character has been found yet (i.e., found == 0), continue to the next iteration.
4. If the current character is not a space, increment the ans variable to count the length of the last word and set found = 1 to indicate that a non-space character has been found.
5. If the current character is a space and at least one non-space character has been found, break the loop since we have counted the last word.
6.Finally, return the value of ans, which represents the length of the last word in the string

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(1)
