# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
python/C/C++(recursive)solution beats 100% with Math proof 
English subtitles are provided, please open it if necessary.
[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kI7CDSHSJpc](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kI7CDSHSJpc)
Let num be a natural number given as follows
$$ num=\sum_{i}a_i10^i $$
where $0\leq a_i \leq 9$.
It is known the following fact:

Proposition
$$ num\equiv \sum_i a_i (\mod{9}) $$
Proof.
$$ num=\sum_{i}a_i10^i $$
$$=a_0+\sum_{i>0}a_i(10^i-1+1) (\mod{9})$$
$$=\sum_{i}a_i (\mod{9}) (\because 10^i-1=99\cdots 9\equiv0 \bmod{9} )$$ QED.

Let $\sum_{i}a_i$ be substituted into $num$, and apply this Proposition successively, it concludes that the desired digit is (num==0)?0:(num-1)%9+1.   

